IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
*>Identifies the program and provides documentation about it.

PROGRAM-ID.
*>Program name.  This is the most used portion of this division.  

AUTHOR.
*>Program author.

DATE-WRITTEN.
*>When the program was created.

DATE-COMPILED.
*>Often generated automatically.

INSTALLATION.
*>Company or organization.

REMARKS.
*>Documentation comments.

ENVIRONMENT DIVISION.
*>Describes the environment outside the program.

CONFIGURATION SECTION.
*Describes the computer, compiler, and environment.

SOURCE-COMPUTER.
*>Where the program was developed.

OBJECT-COMPUTER.
*>Where the program will run.

SPECIAL-NAMES.
*>Defines special characters, switches, decimal point conventions, etc., and is often omitted on modern programs.

INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION.
*>Defines files and external devices.

FILE-CONTROL.
*>Connects logical COBOL file names to physical files.
*>Example below:
SELECT CUSTOMER-FILE
    ASSIGN TO "CUSTOMER.DAT".

I-O-CONTROL.
*>Advanced file-handling options: buffering, multiple files on same device, file locking behavior.

DATA DIVISION.
*>Defines all data used by the program.

FILE SECTION.
*>Describes records stored in files.

FD CUSTOMER-FILE.
*>This is the file.

01 CUSTOMER-RECORD.
*>This is the record, i.e., one line in the file.

WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
*>Program variables that exist for the entire run.
*>Common examples below:
01 EOF-FLAG.
01 TOTAL-SALES.
01 COUNTER.

LOCAL-STORAGE SECTION.
*>Variables recreated each time a program or routine starts, i.e., some counters reset to a value every time the program reruns before STOP RUN.

LINKAGE SECTION.
*>Where the subprogram identifies shared values from the main program, and vice versa as needed.

SCREEN SECTION.
*>Defines text-based termianl screens.

COMMUNICATION SECTION.
*>Message and communications handling.

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
*>Contains executable instructions.  Everything the program does happens here.

DECLARATIVES
*>Optional error handling and special procedures.

MAIN-SECTION.
*>Groups of related paragraphs, see below.  Less common in modern style, but heavily used in older enterprise code.

READ-CUSTOMER.
*>Paragraphs can be created and defined outside STOP RUN to keep code clean and effiient, i.e., allowing multiple aspects of a program to re-reference a paragraph.

STOP RUN.
*>Entire program stops.  Different from END PROGRAM or GOBACK.
